  ;; PROBLEM 2: Framework stack coherence
  ;;
  ;; The paper claims five lenses. Do they all earn their keep?
  ;;
  ;;   NPT:      YES — structures entire findings section, all 5 patterns mapped
  ;;   Patterns:  YES — the finding format itself, distinctive contribution
  ;;   Sen:       YES — functioning/capability distinction does real work in 6.3, 6.5
  ;;   COM-B:     YES — triangulation in 6.3, clear and bounded
  ;;   Ostrom:    MARGINAL — one paragraph in Background, two sentences in findings
  ;;   Roles:     UNDERDELIVERED — method described, findings barely use it
  ;;
  ;; The question is whether to:
  ;;   (a) Integrate roles properly (add ~1 paragraph per pattern, expand 4.2)
  ;;   (b) Cut roles from Methods and mention coordination complexity as emergent observation
  ;;   (c) Do (a) and also give Ostrom more grounding through the role analysis
  ;;       (Ostrom's design principles MAP to role requirements — monitoring = EV chain)

  ;; PROBLEM 3: The logic model
  ;;
  ;; Currently: patterns compose into causal pathways (success/weak/fail)
  ;; What's missing: WHO must act at each link, WHERE the handoffs break
  ;; The role analysis could annotate the logic model — but currently doesn't
  ;; This is exactly what role_pattern_analysis.md already contains

  ;; PROBLEM 4: The title promises NPT but the distinctive contribution is patterns
  ;;
  ;; NPT is the scaffolding; patterns are the product. The title foregrounds
  ;; the scaffolding. This may be strategic (NPT is known in Implementation Science)
  ;; but a reviewer might say "what's new here beyond applying NPT?"
  ;; The answer is: patterns + tier distinction + implementation modes.
  ;; These need to be defended as the novel contribution, not just NPT application.

  ;; =========================================================================
  ;; COMMUNICATION STRUCTURE: What each section is doing
  ;; =========================================================================

  ;; Section 1 (Introduction):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Establish warrant (two gaps + UKRN as lab)
  ;;   STATUS: Working well. Clear and focused.
  ;;
  ;; Section 2 (Background):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Position lenses; each paragraph sets up something findings will use
  ;;   STATUS: Mostly good. Ostrom paragraph is well-written but underdischarged.
  ;;   Roles are NOT set up here — they appear only in Methods.
  ;;   DECISION POINT: If roles stay, they need a Background paragraph too.
  ;;   If roles go, Ostrom can still stay as a lighter framing device.
  ;;
  ;; Section 3 (Methods):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Describe what was done
  ;;   STATUS: Clear. But role-reanalysis paragraph makes a promise the paper doesn't keep.
  ;;
  ;; Section 4 (Findings):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Present patterns as tension→resolution with evidence
  ;;   STATUS: Strongest section. Each pattern works internally.
  ;;   MISSING: Patterns don't show WHO — they show WHERE (NPT) and HOW (resolution)
  ;;   but not who must coordinate or where the handoffs break.
  ;;
  ;;   Section 4.2 (Cross-cutting):
  ;;   STATUS: Workload and decentralisation themes are solid.
  ;;   Coordination complexity paragraph is the only role-analysis payoff — too thin.
  ;;
  ;; Section 5 (T1 placeholder):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Signal planned work
  ;;   STATUS: Fine as placeholder.
  ;;
  ;; Section 6 (Discussion):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Synthesise, contextualise, extend
  ;;   STATUS: 6.1-6.4 strong. 6.5 is the key section — architecture claim.
  ;;   Role overload sentence in 6.5 is powerful but unsupported by shown analysis.
  ;;   6.6 (implications) is good but could be sharper with role specificity.
  ;;
  ;; Section 7 (Conclusion):
  ;;   FUNCTION: Restate transformation-space thesis
  ;;   STATUS: Good. Clean.

  ;; =========================================================================
  ;; VERDICT: Three options for the role analysis
  ;; =========================================================================

  ;; OPTION A: INTEGRATE PROPERLY
  ;;   - Add Background paragraph on roles (the WHO question)
  ;;   - Add ~1 paragraph per pattern in 4.1.1: "Roles required / Roles absent"
  ;;   - Expand 4.2 coordination complexity into a proper finding with table
  ;;   - Expand 6.5 role overload with specific examples
  ;;   - Annotate logic model description with role requirements
  ;;   COST: ~1500 words added. Paper goes from ~8500 to ~10000.
  ;;   BENEFIT: WHO question properly answered. Ostrom connection grounded.
  ;;           Coordination complexity becomes a real finding not just an observation.
  ;;           Tier distinction gets structural grounding (more actors = harder).
